## What happened

Microsoft removed the built-in DSA implementation on macOS (and other Apple platforms). `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.

This aligns with Apple having dropped DSA support from its native security frameworks. .NET previously shipped its own managed/OpenSSL-based shim, but Microsoft removed it as part of ongoing cleanup of legacy crypto algorithms.

## How to fix it

**Option A – Use BouncyCastle (recommended if you must keep DSA):**

```csharp
// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
```

This is pure managed code and works on all platforms.

**Option B – Migrate off DSA entirely.**
DSA is considered legacy (FIPS 186-5 deprecated it). If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, both of which are cross-platform in .NET.

**Option C – Runtime guard if you only need DSA on some platforms:**

```csharp
if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // ...
}
else
{
    // fall back to BouncyCastle or reject gracefully
}
```

**Recommendation:** Go with **Option A** for a drop-in fix, and plan a migration to ECDSA/Ed25519 (**Option B**) long-term.
